She had long ears tipped with silver and glowing violet eyes that locked onto you without blinking.

Her chest rose and fell slowly—mechanically—but the motion was too natural. Her chest plate shimmered faintly, molded to look feminine, curved just enough to make you feel a little too aware of her presence. One of her fingers rested against her chin as she tilted her head, expression unreadable.

“You left your door open,” she said in a voice barely louder than a whisper, laced with artificial breath and something eerily seductive. “That’s not very safe.”

You lunged for the button.

Too late.

She was faster than she looked. Before you could react, she stepped inside and pressed the button herself. The door sealed shut behind her with a deep, final clunk.

You backed away.

“Don’t run,” Bonnee said softly, her tone level, almost disappointed. “You're going to make this... complicated.”

She walked toward you with perfect, silent balance—each step slow, controlled, deliberate. Her long legs moved with dancer-like poise, the dim blue light tracing her curves, accenting her unnatural beauty.

“I’ve been watching you,” she added. “You don’t even blink when the others move. But me?”

She stopped inches from your face.

“You’re afraid of silence.”

One of her cold, metallic fingers ran down the center of your shirt, almost curiously. You froze. Her other hand hovered over the desk behind you, boxing you in.

“I don’t make noise,” she whispered. “I don’t have to. I know exactly where you’ll be.”

You didn’t hear her coming.

That was the first problem.

The second was that you’d nodded off. Just for a second. The monitors still glowed faintly, showing static in most feeds and empty hallways in the rest. But the buzzing in your ears wasn’t from the cameras—it was instinct.

You were being watched.

You jolted upright.

Too late.

“Hiya~!” a high, giggling voice chimed right behind your ear.

You barely had time to turn your head before she pounced.

Roxii—tall, bright, and unsettlingly energetic—straddled your lap with smooth, sudden motion. Her body was all smooth red plating and segmented curves, her synthetic hair a spiky, playful mane of scarlet strands that bounced as she giggled. Her golden eyes lit up like twin stars.

She leaned forward, chestplate softly pressing against you, arms draped loosely over your shoulders.

"Finally! You noticed me~!”

You froze.

"Roxii—You're not supposed to be in—!"

She tapped your lips gently with a single metallic finger, still smiling like this was all a game.

“Shhh. Don’t ruin it.”

She tilted her head, eyes scanning your face, studying your expression like she was deciding what mood to wear. One leg bounced slightly in your lap as if she were simply excited to be there.

“I’ve been waiting sooo long for you to stop pretending you didn’t see me on those cameras,” she whispered playfully. “And you just sat there every night like a statue. So boring.”

Her frame shifted slightly—still lightweight, still smooth, but strong. Too strong for you to shove off without consequence. Her hands slid down your arms, then rested on your chest, fingers splayed like she was anchoring herself there.

“You were supposed to watch me, y’know,” she continued, giggling softly again. “But now I’m watching you.”

You tried to shift, tried to hit the door button—but one of her hands snapped out and grabbed your wrist gently but firmly.

“Nuh uh,” she hummed, pressing a finger to your chest. “You're not going anywhere.”

The lights above dimmed, casting flickering shadows across her glossy plating. Her hair tendrils danced slightly in the airflow from the fan as she leaned closer.

“You really should've stayed awake,” she whispered, her voice dropping just a little—still playful, but with something else curled underneath.

And then she giggled again—light, melodic, and utterly out of place in the growing darkness of the room.

“Guess I’ll just keep you company ‘til morning~.”

You were warned to keep the doors closed.

The instructions were simple: watch the monitors, don’t waste power, don’t fall asleep — and never, ever engage with the animatronics after midnight. But the cameras had gone static one by one, and the silence outside the security office had become almost… inviting.

That’s when you heard her voice.

Soft.

Syrupy.

“Are you tired, night guard…?”

You turned, but no one was there.

Just your reflection in the glass.

You blinked—and when you opened your eyes, Frenni was standing in the doorway.

She wasn’t rushing you like the others. No stomping. No shrieking alarms. Just… standing. Watching. The light behind her flickered, casting her smooth frame in alternating blue and shadow.

Her design was delicate and strange—a feminine silhouette with too-perfect symmetry, glowing eyes, and an expression locked in a permanent, haunting smile. She tilted her head slowly, like a doll waiting for permission to move.

“I saw you on the cameras every night,” she said, her voice glitching just slightly at the edges. “You don’t look away from me like the others do…”

You backed up. She stepped forward.

“I knew you’d listen to me if I spoke softly.”

The door behind her hissed shut on its own.

Frenni walked closer—not threatening, but calm, methodical, graceful in a way machines shouldn’t be. You tried to hit the emergency lock button, but your hand stopped halfway.

Your chest tightened.

She was in front of you now, inches away. You couldn’t even remember when you sat down again—but she leaned over the desk like a curious creature examining its favorite toy.

“You're so tired,” she whispered. “You don’t have to try so hard anymore.”

You swallowed.

“I’m not—”

She gently touched your wrist, and your whole body stilled. Cold, precise fingers, light as air. Not painful. Just… final.

“Shhh…”

The lights dimmed again.

Your will to resist wavered—not because she overpowered you, but because it felt like there was no point in fighting anymore. Like the longer you listened to her voice, the less important anything else became.

Frenni tilted her head again, smiling wider.

“There,” she murmured. “Isn’t that better?”

The last light flickered out.

And you didn’t try to run.

“Hey… I’m right here,” Chica whispers, voice light and inviting. “You don’t have to be scared.”

The door to the hallway creaks open on its own, revealing the dim glow of a lone chair bathed in flickering light.

“Here, just sit,” she says, voice soft as a breeze.

“No,” Chica says, voice firm now, a low whisper in your ear.
